{
  "query": "To restore peatlands afforested for commercial forestry, how does simply cutting the trees compare to cutting trees and also rewetting the peat?",
  "relevant_summary": "Cutting/removing forest plantations alone: Three studies reported increased cover of some herbs (including cottongrasses and sedges), while one reported no effect on other herb species; forest-characteristic moss cover decreased in one study; Sphagnum cover decreased over three years in a drained rich fen but increased over eight years in partly rewetted rich fens; total plant species richness increased in rich fens, with a much smaller effect in rewetted plots than in drained plots [1731]. Cutting/removing trees combined with rewetting: In fens, two studies found no change in overall plant community composition and one reported only a small effect, while two site-comparison studies in bogs and fens found composition shifted away from drained, forested conditions; wetland-characteristic plants increased in abundance; Sphagnum cover increased in two studies, showed no effect in one, and mixed effects depending on site or species in two others; non\u2011Sphagnum or forest-characteristic mosses decreased in three studies, with one study finding no effect of thinning/rewetting on forest mosses; herb cover (including cottongrasses and sedges) increased in multiple studies, though one site lost rare cottongrass and saw reduced purple moor grass; vegetation structure responses included increased ground vegetation height in one bog study, no change in canopy height in one fen study, and fewer tall trees for 1\u20133 years in two studies; plant species richness increased in two Swedish fen studies but showed no effect on richness or diversity in two Finnish fen studies [1732].",
  "action_ids": [
    "1731",
    "1732"
  ]
}

